ce:section.ce:para:
Further investigation was conducted to compare the properties of bismuth(III) oxyiodide before and after photocatalytic reaction in aqueous phase. The elemental contents and chemical character of Ti, Sr and Bi atoms in surface layer of pure BiOI and BiOI_ TiO2/SrTiO3_1 (sample before photocatalytic reaction) and BiOI_TiO2/SrTiO3_2 (sample after photocatalytic reaction) are presented in Table 2
                        . The chemical character of titanium and strontium originated from the TiO2/SrTiO3 matrix is similar to that presented in our last published paper [52]. The Bi 4f spectra recorded for pure BiOI and for both BiOI_TiO2/SrTiO3samples revealed two chemical states of Bi, Bi° and Bi3+, represented by the Bi 4f7/2 signals at 1570 and 159.5 eV, respectively (see Fig. 7
                        ). The XPS data collected in Table 2 and the Bi 4f HR spectra in Fig. 7 clearly show that the Bi0 fraction becomes more pronounced in the Bi 4f spectrum recorded on the BiOI_TiO2/SrTiO3_1 sample. That indicates the partial chemical transformation of BiOI at the step of BiOI_TiO2/SrTiO3 sample preparation occurs. The Bi/I atomic % ratio evaluated for the BiOI_TiO2/SrTiO3_1 sample was found to be much larger than for pure BiOI (Table 2) what confirm also the chemical interaction of BiOI with TiO2/SrTiO3 matrix. The XPS spectra recorded for the BiOI_TiO2/SrTiO3_2 sample, after photocatalytic reaction, disclose the relative surface contents of Sr, Bi and C atoms to be slightly smaller and the oxygen and indium to be larger to compare with the sample before reaction (Table 2). The Bi/I atomic % ratio becomes smaller after reaction but remains still larger than for pure BiOI. It should be noticed that the Bi° which occurs in the composite before irradiation process was oxidized to Bi3+ during the irradiation with visible light range in phenol solution. As a result the relative contribution of the Bi3+ fraction increases reaching the level close to pure BiOI (Table 2).
